<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5822&amp;p=53810#p53810</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5822&amp;p=53810#p53810"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Camp demo 1: Tall Pixel]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5822&amp;p=53810#p53810"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />I don't know if many people are having enough CHR space problems to justify a complex solution like this.<br /></div><br />I am. Camp (deluxe version) has an opening cut scene, but the CHR RAM on its SNROM board has only 6.5 KiB of CHR RAM left after subtracting 96 tiles for text glyphs. I can possibly get it down to 4 or 5 KiB in the ROM using something like the Codemasters codec, but I still need to decompress it for display.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Complex because it doesn't look as good with refresh rates other than 60 Hz<br /></div><br />As I wrote in the README, I don't have a 50 Hz NES to test with.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />and uses timed code specific to NTSC consoles. If it was possible to make it work in PAL or NTSC automatically it would be great.<br /></div><br />That would be a matter of detecting the PAL NES at boot time and switch to the loops designed for 341/3.2 cycle operation. <strong>I can remember</strong> Dwedit saying Codemasters games do that, but they fail on Dendy which has the same CPU:PPU ratio as NTSC but more scanlines per frame. So to be compatible with all three variants in one program, we'd need to check for the frame period being close to 312*341/3.2, that is, 33200 to 33300 CPU cycles. This way both 262*341/3 (NTSC) and 312*341/3 (Dendy) are detected as 341/3 systems.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />What's up with the top half of the "l" in "Pixel"? Why's it pink?<br /></div><br /><img src="http://www.overcaffeinated.org/images/soda-pop/sprite-zero-1.jpg" alt="Image" /><br />In a real game, the pink part would be drawn either with the behind bit turned on or in a color matching the backdrop.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Wed Dec 09, 2009 9:50 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
