<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[tepples]]></name></author>
<updated>2009-12-09T20:42:14-07:00</updated>
<published>2009-12-09T20:42:14-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5822&amp;p=53808#p53808</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5822&amp;p=53808#p53808"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Camp demo 1: Tall Pixel]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5822&amp;p=53808#p53808"><![CDATA[
In the process of developing the project codenamed <strong>Camp</strong>, I have come up with several proof-of-concept demos. This one is called Tall Pixel. It demonstrates a way to stretch still images vertically by a factor of 3/2, using mixed $2006/$2005 writes and timed code, so that the CHR data for your cut scenes takes 33% less space. Tested on <a href="http://packages.ubuntu.com/karmic/fceu" class="postlink">FCEU Karmic</a> and on an NTSC NES + PowerPak.<br /><br /><strong>Tall Pixel (NTSC version)</strong><br /><a href="http://pics.pineight.com/nes/tall_pixel.zip" class="postlink">Download NROM binary and CC65+Python source</a><p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Wed Dec 09, 2009 8:42 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
